<TITLE> Indian left says will not support Congress-led govt </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, May 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. (The sources are mentioned in brackets) Prakash Karat, chief of the Communist Party of India (Marxist) said the left parties would not support a Congress-led coalition government, a day after Rahul Gandhi, said the Congress was confident of the communist parties' support after election. The support of the left parties could prove crucial if the Congress want to regain power after polls, which experts say could be tight. (NDTV news channel) The Congress party moved swiftly to pacify its allies, including Mamata Banerjee, the leader of the West Bengal-based Trinamool Congress, after she objected to Rahul Gandhi warming to the left. Veerappa Moily, senior leader of the Congress party said, the pact with Trinamool and other allies was "very precious". The Congress, which struggled to keep its allies together before the staggered election got underway, is desperately trying to keep them happy, as it attempts to regain power at the centre. (The Times of India) WHAT THE NEWSPAPERS SAY The Congress central command may see the left as partners in any post-poll combination, but in West Bengal and Kerala, the Congress is smelling blood. "Sonia Gandhi, on a visit there, accused the Bengal government of running a dictatorship and in Kerala, with pundits predicting a white-washed red brigade, the Congress has upped the ante, going after the left hammer and tongs
